# A/B Testing (controlled experiment)
############################################################################################
#
############################################################################################
# Application of A/B testing:
    # e.g. Amazon could use A/B testing to test whether different price is leading to more profit, whether different webside design is getting more customers,
        # whether different recommendation algorithm lead to better clicks, etc.
    # e.g. Netflix could test whether new algorithm is recommending more relevant videos, whether a website design is better, etc.
############################################################################################
# Designing of A/B testing:
    # sample_size >= 16 * sigma ^2 / delta ^ 2
    # delta == minimum detectable effect (e.g. 0.1% increase in revenue)
    # number_of_days >= 14 and or number_of_days = sample_size / number_of_users 

# Multiple Testing Problem:
    # 



# Z distribution --> X_bar ~ Normal_Distribution(miu, sigma^2/ n)
    # or Z = (x_bar - miu)/ (sigma/ n^0.5) ~ Normal_Distribution(0, 1) 
    # Based on the central limit theorem, when the number of observations in the sample is big enough (n > 30), the distribution of the sample average would 
        # follow a normal distribution
    
    # In the real world, it's very hard to get the sigma of the population, therefore, we normally use the sample standard deviation to represent population sigma.
    
    # t distribution --> t = (x_bar - miu)/ (standard_deviasion/ n^0.5) ~ t(n-1)
        # degree of freedom = n - 1
        
        # e.g. x1 = 1, x2 = 2, x3 = 3, if you know x_bar, you would know x3, so that degree of freedom = n - 1
            # 







